values.comments:
Professor Wolfson’s class was thought to be very “philosophy based,” focusing mostly on “theoretical issues.” Much of the class was based upon weekly responses, student presentations, and class participation in discussions on nine assigned texts. One student found the reading material to contain the “same messages” and the weekly blog posts to be “somewhat redundant." Students generally seemed to think class discussions could have used more “structure” and “instructor input.” While one student thought the discussions “often seemed rushed and forced,” most others tended to “enjoy” how they could “openly debate issues surrounding public education.”

Students appreciated Professor Wolfson’s “insight” in linking the “theoretical readings to tangible social problems” and his “willingness to engage the opinion of each individual student.”&#8232;&#8232;

As an introduction course, this class was “highly” recommended to those looking for a “comprehensive overview of educational disparities across lines of race and class.” For some, this course was “very different” from what was expected, but it certainly had its “high points.” This course is cross-listed with EDUC 202 and fulfills the Cultural Diversity in the US college requirement. It is also an academically based community service course.
